<TITLE> Govt to fix media policy on defence coverage </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 23 (bdnews24.com)--The government has moved to make a media policy on the coverage of news on the military and defence affairs, the prime minister has said. Sheikh Hasina said her administration is reorganising the Inter-Service Public Relations (ISPR) Directorate to make modern and effective, according to governmnet-run news agency BSS. She made the remarks at the Formation Commanders' Conference-2009 of Bangladesh Army at the Army Headquarters in Dhaka Cantonment on Monday. Referring to recent propaganda centering the army in a section of newspapers and TV channels, she said any negative remarks or discussion on the army hurt the morale of all the military personnel. The prime minister urged the army men not to get confused with propaganda and hopes that they would do their job sincerely and honestly. She called upon the army to stand together to foil any attempt against the nation by maintaining discipline, unity and fellow feelings. Hasina asked the army to keep full confidence in the law, judicial system and administration. "The existing process could be time-consuming, but it is possible to achieve sustainable and permanent solution only through this process," she said. Hasina referred to her election pledge to reiterate that her government will build a modern and strong army. "Our main objective is to attain economic prosperity quickly maintaining the country's internal stability." Army chief General Mohammad Abdul Mubeen received the prime minister. Her defence adviser Tarique Ahmed Siddique, a retired major general, was among those prese
